name: Maj. James Thomas, KC
tagline: Fearless leader who silenced six infiltrators
fullStory: Major James Thomas was an officer of 10 Sikh LI, Sikh Light Infantry, known for exceptional courage in counter-insurgency operations in Jammu & Kashmir. He was posthumously awarded the Kirti Chakra for eliminating multiple terrorists during an anti-infiltration operation in Poonch in 2006.
backstory: Born on 6 September 1976 in Bikaner, Rajasthan, he was commissioned into 10 Sikh LI and became known as a dedicated field leader in highrisk areas. During 2005-2006 his battalion was deployed in J&K, where he frequently led operations against infiltrating terrorists along the Line of Control.

operations.name: Poonch Anti-Infiltration Operation
operations.description: Leading an ambush near the LoC in Poonch, J&K, he intercepted infiltrating terrorists, moved forward under heavy fire, used grenades and small arms, and killed four terrorists in the initial close-quarter engagement despite sustaining serious splinter injuries.

operations.name: Poonch Anti-Infiltration Operation (final phase)
operations.description: While grievously wounded, he noticed two more terrorists trying to outflank his position; he crawled towards them, continued firing and throwing grenades, and neutralised both before succumbing to his injuries, taking the total to six terrorists killed.

name: Nk. Digendra Kumar Paraswal, MVC, SM
regiment: 2nd Battalion, The Rajputana Rifles (2 Rajputana Rifles)
tagline: Cobra of Tololing, Kargil War hero
fullStory: Naik Digendra Kumar Paraswal is a highly decorated Kargil War veteran of 2 Rajputana Rifles, awarded the Maha Vir Chakra and Sena Medal for exceptional bravery in battle.
backstory: Born on 3 July 1969 in Village Jharli, Sikar district, Rajasthan, he joined 2 Rajputana Rifles in 1985 and served as a commando in multiple high-risk operations, including the IPKF mission in Sri Lanka.

operations.name: IPKF operation, Sri Lanka
operations.description: As part of the Indian Peace Keeping Force, carried heavy ammunition by boat through rebel-held areas, freed surrounded Indian troops, destroyed an enemy ammunition dump, and reportedly killed several militants in close combat.

operations.name: Assault on Tololing, Dras sector, Kargil War
operations.description: Commanded the Light Machine Gun group during the assault to capture heavily fortified Pakistani positions on Tololing; though wounded in the arm, he kept firing one-handed to pin down the enemy, enabling his company to close in, clear multiple bunkers in hand-to-hand fighting, and secure the objective.

operations.name: Kargil War tally, Dras sector
operations.description: Across the Tololing engagement he is credited in open sources with killing 48 enemy soldiers single-handedly while his body armour took 18 hits, a feat that has since become part of his battlefield legend.

name: Sep. Gurtej Singh, VrC
regiment: 3rd Battalion, The Punjab Regiment (3 Punjab), Ghatak Platoon
tagline: Lion of Galwan, fearless to the end
fullStory: Sepoy Gurtej Singh was a 23-year-old Ghatak commando of 3 Punjab who attained martyrdom during the violent clash with Chinese troops in Galwan Valley, Ladakh, on 15 June 2020.
backstory: Hailing from Birewala Dogran village in Budladha tehsil of Mansa district, Punjab, he joined the Indian Army in 2018 and quickly earned a reputation for exceptional physical courage and devotion to duty.

operations.name: Operation Snow Leopard, Galwan Valley clash
operations.description: As part of 3 Punjabs Ghatak Platoon reinforcing 16 Bihar, he engaged in hand-to-hand combat with PLA soldiers, reportedly dragging four enemy soldiers off a ridge, climbing back despite severe head and neck injuries, and then using his kirpan and captured weapons to kill a total of 12 enemy soldiers before being fatally wounded.

name: Hav. Jassa Singh, VrC
fullStory: Havildar Jassa Singh was a non-commissioned officer of 14 Punjab who fought with extraordinary courage during the 1965 Indo-Pak War while defending Indian positions on the Fazilka-Sulaimanke road sector.
backstory: Serving in 14 Punjab (Nabha Akal), he was part of the unit deployed in Punjab during Operation Riddle in 1965, where Pakistani forces repeatedly attacked Indian defences along the international border.

operations.name: Defence of Fazilka-Sulaimanke road, Punjab
operations.description: When Pakistani troops attacked his companys defended locality supported by a Medium Machine Gun post, Havildar Jassa Singh charged the enemy Browning MG position, shot dead the gunner, and killed five more enemy soldiers in close combat, even after his own weapon malfunctioned. With his rifle out of action, he grabbed an ammunition box and used it as an improvised weapon, bludgeoning two additional enemy soldiers to death, thus single-handedly eliminating eight enemies and breaking the attack on his platoons position.

name: Sub Maj. & Hony Lt. Har Singh, VrC & Bar
rank: Subedar-Major & Honorary Lieutenant (then Jemadar/Platoon Commander at the time of first Vir Chakra)
regiment: Kumaon Regiment (from Almora region of Kumaon, Uttarakhand)
fullStory: Har Singh was a legendary platoon commander from the Kumaon Regiment, hailing from the Almora region, who earned the Vir Chakra twice for extraordinary leadership and courage against heavy odds.
backstory: Known in regimental lore as a tough field leader of raw but determined Kumaoni soldiers, he rose through the ranks to become Subedar-Major and Honorary Lieutenant, symbolising the fighting spirit of the Kumaon hills.

operations.name: Ambush against enemy column
operations.description: Leading a platoon of about 21 newly trained soldiers, Har Singh encountered a force of roughly 50 enemy troops; he told his men this was his chance to judge them as fighting soldiers, laid a close-range ambush that opened fire at about 25 yards, followed it with a bayonet charge, killed around 25 enemy soldiers and captured three, including their commander, earning his first Vir Chakra.

operations.name: False attack and capture of snowy feature
operations.description: About three months later he was ordered to lead a false attack towards a strongly held feature in deep snow 4-5 feet high to divert the enemy while the main force attacked elsewhere; instead, he personally led his men up the slope, seized the feature, reorganised his platoons on the objective and repulsed two determined counter-attacks, actions for which he received a Bar to the Vir Chakra (second award).

name: Sub. Surinder Singh, AC
tagline: Lone JCO who felled six terrorists
fullStory: Subedar Surinder Singh was a JCO of 3 Sikh who displayed exceptional gallantry during counter-insurgency operations in Rajouri sector, Jammu & Kashmir, on 3 March 2002, and was posthumously awarded the Ashoka Chakra, Indias highest peacetime gallantry award.
backstory: He hailed from Jadh village in Reasi tehsil of Jammu district, J&K, and served with 3 Sikh Regiment during Operation Rakshak/Parakram along the Line of Control, where his leadership and courage became an example for his unit.

operations.name: Operation Rakshak / Operation Parakram, Rajouri sector, J&K
operations.description: While in charge of a search party near the LoC, he allowed a group of terrorists to close in, shot one at close range, then led a pursuit as they scattered into jungle and into a house in village Tarala, repeatedly exposing himself to fire, climbing onto a roof to use explosives and grenades, and continuing to fight despite multiple splinter injuries, ultimately accounting for four to six terrorists before succumbing to his wounds; his men later neutralised additional terrorists and removed the threat to the post.

name: Maj. Kaluvakolan Bhushan, SC, SM
tagline: 9 Para SF officer who felled five terrorists
fullStory: Major Kaluvakolan Bhushan is a highly decorated Special Forces officer of 9 Para (SF) who led an Alpha Team raid on a Lashkar-e-Taiba hideout in Kupwara district, Jammu & Kashmir, on 26 August 1995.
backstory: Commissioned into the Parachute Regiment, he served with 9 Para (SF) during intense counter-terrorist operations in the Kashmir Valley and became known for aggressive small-team leadership in high-risk raids against heavily armed militants.

operations.name: Kupwara Raid on LeT Hideout, Lolab Valley
operations.description: As leader of an Alpha Team of 9 Para (SF), he planned and executed a night raid on a Lashkar-e-Taiba cave-type hideout at high altitude in Kupwara district, closing in under difficult terrain and using grenades and automatic fire to neutralise the position. During the operation, when a militant using darkness and cover pinned his team, Major Bhushan advanced at grave personal risk, overpowered the terrorist in hand-to-hand combat, physically lifted him, and threw him down a precipice, contributing to a total of five militants eliminated in the action.

name: Maj. Avinash Singh Bhadauria, KC
regiment: 18 Madras, The Madras Regiment; on deputation to 8 Rashtriya Rifles (8 RR)
tagline: Major who single-handedly felled four terrorists
fullStory: Major Avinash Singh Bhadauria was an officer of 18 Madras serving with 8 Rashtriya Rifles in Jammu & Kashmir, who displayed remarkable bravery during a counter-insurgency operation in Doda district on 28 September 2001.
backstory: Born on 14 December 1971 in Kanpur, Uttar Pradesh, he joined the National Defence Academy in 1990, was commissioned into 18 Madras in June 1994, and later volunteered for deputation to 8 RR, where he quickly earned a reputation for calm, front-line leadership in operations.

operations.name: Counter-insurgency operation, Hanch area, Doda district, J&K
operations.description: Acting on specific intelligence about heavily armed militants, he led a search-and-destroy mission, cordoned the suspected hideout, and engaged the terrorists in a fierce firefight, personally killing multiple militants at close range despite heavy incoming fire. Despite being grievously wounded, he continued to fight after being , directing his men and ensuring the operations success; he ultimately succumbed to his injuries, having single-handedly accounted for up to four terrorists and inspiring his troops to eliminate the remaining threat.
